    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1913004949" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1913004949" />
    <a title="Hugh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32318315-hugh"><img alt="Hugh" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1466451007p2/32318315.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1913004949?book_show_action=true">Mar 21, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hugh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hugh" href="/user/show/32318315-hugh">Hugh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781447289593" href="/book/show/31816207-2666">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32318315-hugh?shelf=translations">translations</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32318315-hugh?shelf=read-2018">read-2018</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32318315-hugh?shelf=favourites">favourites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32318315-hugh?shelf=mookse-madness">mookse-madness</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32318315-hugh?shelf=modern-lit">modern-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32318315-hugh?shelf=modern-classics">modern-classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1913004949" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10993633207576078699">A monumental novel, which is rightly considered to be one of the most essential novels of the 21st century. It covers such a wide range of characters, places and subjects that it is very difficult to review quickly, and I am unlikely to have anything very new to say about it. This is my first experience of reading Bolaño, and this book is the subject of a discussion which I am currently leading for the <b>21st Century Literature</b> group <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/topic/group_folder/359672' rel='nofollow noopener'>here</a><br/><br/>Overall I found this a very stimulating reading experience, </span>
  <span id="freeText10993633207576078699" style="display:none">A monumental novel, which is rightly considered to be one of the most essential novels of the 21st century. It covers such a wide range of characters, places and subjects that it is very difficult to review quickly, and I am unlikely to have anything very new to say about it. This is my first experience of reading Bolaño, and this book is the subject of a discussion which I am currently leading for the <b>21st Century Literature</b> group <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/topic/group_folder/359672" rel="nofollow noopener">here</a><br /><br />Overall I found this a very stimulating reading experience, but not one without its frustrations. The book consists of five parts, each of which can be regarded as a novel in its own right - these are largely self-contained but there are links - all five are at least partly set in Santa Teresa, a fictional city in the Mexican desert close to the American border. Bolaño, like Thomas Pynchon, seems to have been an expert on many diverse fields, and the book's structure is very loose, with frequent digressions and anecdotes. Minor characters are often introduced over several pages, and then forgotten. <br /><br />The first book (The Part About the Critics) is a satire set in the academic world. It concerns four scholars (French, Spanish, Italian and British) who are leading experts on the fictional German novelist Benno van Archimboldi, and their quest to find the elusive writer. All four are referred to mainly by their surnames, and they are involved in a tangled three way romance. They meet Archimboldi's publisher, the aged widow Frau Bubis, one of the few living people who has met the writer, who is able to tell them very little except that he is unusually tall. Their quest then takes them to Santa Teresa<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[, but they fail to find Archimboldi <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. They hear about the many killings of young women and girls in and around Santa Teresa (part 4) and meet Amolfitano, a Spanish/Catalan academic who lives there, and is the subject of Part Two. At the end of this section very little is resolved other than the ménage, and none of the critics appear in any of the later parts.<br /><br />The second book (The Part about Amolfitano) is the shortest, and despite its title is largely about Amolfitano's ex-wife Lola, who leaves him to pursue a homosexual artist who resides in a lunatic asylum. Amolfitano and his daughter Rosa move from Barcelona to Mexico and settle in Santa Teresa. Once again the section ends without much of a resolution.<br /><br />At the start of the third book (The Part About Fate) we meet the American journalist Oscar Fate, who works for a largely black new York magazine as an interviewer. He meets an old Black Panther leader who is now a food writer. After many digressions he is asked to cover a fight in Santa Teresa between a local heavyweight and an up-and-coming New York fighter, and is sucked into the world of Rosa Amalfitano and also meets a journalist who is investigating the killings, with whom he visits a tall German suspect in prison. <br /><br />The first three books account for just over a third of the whole.<br /><br />The fourth book (The Part About the Crimes) is a challenge to read, as its 284 pages largely consist of a relentless and very repetitive list of the killings and the largely fruitless investigations. The prime suspect is the tall German Klaus Haas, but the killings continue after he is imprisoned. The main narrative is interrupted with many lengthy and entertaining digressions, for example a discussion about phobias which allows Bolaño scope to indulge his linguistic interests, a similar one on different types of fortune telling and a rather tasteless list of sexist "jokes" as told by the local policemen. Once again very little is resolved.<br /><br />The final book (The Part About Archimboldi) is also very long. It tells the life story of the writer whose work the Critics are obsessed with, from his birth in 1920 up to his decision to visit Santa Teresa, where the book ends. His life (as Hans Reiter) begins in Prussia, where as a boy he is more interested in underwater exploration than learning. After a few casual jobs including one as the servant to an aristocratic family, the War begins and he is enlisted in an Infantry regiment, where his picaresque adventures include a night in Dracula's Romanian castle, discovering the notebooks of a purged Russian writer Ansky (whose life is explored in another lengthy digression - Ansky's notes also cover his interest in the 16th century painter Arcimboldo, who is most famous for his paintings in which faces are composed of fruit and other objects) and his experiences in an American camp where he hears the story of a relatively minor Nazi war criminal Sammer, who he later admits to having murdered. After the war he finds himself in Cologne, where he starts writing. He believes that he is still under suspicion for Sammer's murder so he adopts the pseudonym Archimboldi. His work is published by Bubis, an elderly Jew who has returned to Hamburg to restart his publishing business. Frau Bubis turns out to be one of the aristocrats Reiter worked for as a youth. In the last part of the book we meet Reiter's sister Lotte<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[, and discover that Klaus Haas is her son <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />Bolaño considered the book to be unfinished, but this is not apparent to the reader, and the stories' episodic structure and Bolaño's view that it could be published as five self-contained books make it rather resistant to conventional plot resolution. A fascinating book, at times frustrating to read, but one which would almost certainly be worth revisiting.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10993633207576078699" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


