  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1337323904" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1337323904" />
    <a title="Christopher Howard" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19905066-christopher-howard"><img alt="Christopher Howard" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1486417290p2/19905066.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1337323904?book_show_action=true">Nov 28, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christopher Howard" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christopher Howard" href="/user/show/19905066-christopher-howard">Christopher Howard</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780374100148" href="/book/show/3115359-2666">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19905066-christopher-howard?shelf=mexico">mexico</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19905066-christopher-howard?shelf=bolano">bolano</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1337323904" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8773688449897091691">This will be a bad review of this book. They are really only notes. You will only maybe get it if you<br/><blockquote>1. have read the book<br/>2. know me personally<br/>3. are interested in things I am interested in<br/>4. are interested in things I think Bolaño was interested in<br/>5. enjoy reading something you know could be expressed more simply.<br/></blockquote><br/>This was a personal read for me because of course I was there when I read it. This felt however like a very impersonal book. Or at least a book concerned (and genuinely concerned) with</span>
  <span id="freeText8773688449897091691" style="display:none">This will be a bad review of this book. They are really only notes. You will only maybe get it if you<br /><blockquote>1. have read the book<br />2. know me personally<br />3. are interested in things I am interested in<br />4. are interested in things I think Bolaño was interested in<br />5. enjoy reading something you know could be expressed more simply.<br /></blockquote><br />This was a personal read for me because of course I was there when I read it. This felt however like a very impersonal book. Or at least a book concerned (and genuinely concerned) with impersonality. That is one aspect of it. <br /><br />There is a lot of death in this novel. It is impersonal. It occurs in the Sonoran Desert. (Lots of other places too.) The Mexico-US border is a large entity. Bad things happen there sometimes. When I was originally reading this book with good reader friend Dave, and by chance I was driving through the great concavity called Texas, near Ciudad Juarez, (the Real City from which Bolaño wrote Santa Teresa into Infrarealism), Dave informed me that he had read that a real life border patrol agent not too far from my proximity felt the compulsion to do some of the brutal things that fictional men do to women (and girls) in this novel.<br /><br />At another time, Right Now, a Sonora comes across the sky of Mexican border city, Tijuana. US Border Agents who are just following orders are lobbing tear gas canisters at migratory women and children who make up a good chunk of a "caravan" of migrants seeking sanctuary from misery. There are many versions of this story, of course. But this happened. In a real place. Not in a piece of writing, fictional or otherwise.<br /><br />A sense of geography aids in one’s reading of this novel as well as in everything else in one’s life. But I do notice that in trying to contextualize Bolaño’s novel, one finds oneself in an ever-growing labyrinth of stories, histories, myths. Everything becomes significant. I can even find myself compelled, or entitled, to mention an anecdote that has seemingly nothing to do with anything… such as in 2016 musician Beth Orton, while filming a music video in Joshua Tree National Park for a song called “1973” vibrantly, joyously spray painted an ancient Joshua Tree, hydra in the desert, living its life for—let’s say comfortably—more than a hundred years, until someone came along thinking it would look better as a simulacrum for a bunch of balloons. Once Orton caught flak for ignorantly destroying nature, she said she was sorry, but she thought the tree was already dead. <br /><br />(Day Glo Good. Life Bad.)<br /><br /><br />This was a very personal book—for Bolaño. Or so that is what everyone in Bolaño studies will say regarding this book. That Bolaño was racing against Death itself in mastering its completion (in more than one sense and to more than one end). A romantic notion, surely, and one might wonder whether Bolaño was tickling his own fancy with that notion. I doubt it.<br /><br />What is the value of <i>2666</i> for Bolaño? Maybe it became his infinite text. His labyrinth. Bolaño reputedly made the switch from poet to novelist to make money to support his family. Feverously writing books which are at the same time incredibly self-indulgent and incredibly outreaching, you might say he was Booking Bad. The book consumed him, you might say. No, I don’t think so. <br /><br />The first part of this book (it is broken into five) is the Part about the Critics and immediately the reader can see Bolaño lampooning those whose eyes never leave the page. All the while, Bolaño’s lampoon seems inaccessible to the inexcessable. Only those whose eyes look long enough for the image to change will see anything. Which means that trying to point it out to anyone whose eyes haven’t looked long enough will reveal only wisps of air and will make the reader, the pointer, look deranged. Maybe this is Infrarealism. Maybe Infrarealism is nothing.<br /><br />I’ll be plain about it: I do not know as much Latin American history as I should. Perhaps others also enjoy reading books like <i>2666</i> because they feel like historical anthologies of invisible (to them) cities, whose inhabitants it seems no one around has noticed even though the inhabitants have always been around. Reading a text whose historical context is entirely foreign is like opening a wooden Russian doll and finding an even larger wooden Russian doll, and upon finding this, you cannot be sure whether you should investigate the workings of the original Russian doll, or whether you should see if things will get even bigger. Reading Bolaño, one should know though, at least when it comes to his two Big Novels is like getting engulfed in the venture of opening these anticartesian wooden dolls, getting comfortable with the new rules, and then on one repetition, finding inside not a larger doll, but a smaller one, which looks different from the others, although it still seems like they belong together, and wouldn’t it be nice to see if—yep—there’s a bigger one in here too, and we’re back in business and wouldn’t it be nice to try to organize all of these dolls which are making quite a mess of whatever dimension this is occurring in, and once you actually consider doing something like sorting all of the Russian dolls by size, color, style, so that the Russian dolls look normal and make sense now—they act the way you expect them to act—you step back and wonder how that could possibly compare with the beauty of how things were originally stacked. But that’ll only happen if that’s what one wants.<br /><br />If one wants to sort the dolls, one should find a review that says “in part one, in part two, in part three, et cetera” but I still find myself arguing “In part one in part two in part three et cetera.” I jotted down the name and significance of every cultural reference I noticed in this book. Some are Lilliputian in their elaboration; others are glaring, bonking you on the head with the grace of a rainbow-colored lead balloon, and they feel like a setup. That is how Part One of this book treats you. It is a detective novel where the detectives are taking the wrong case. It is a dark book, but it is also a lampoon of a dark book. This, I think, is what makes <i>2666</i> impersonal. That there is a crude and disgusting man telling a crude and disgusting joke over the cacophony of crude and disgusting jokes going unnoticed, creating real horror.<br /><br />In Part Two, The Part About Amalfitano, we see Mexico from the perspective of a <s>Mexican</s> Chilean in Exile in Mexico. (A mal fit, I know.) Maybe it's important to point out that Part One is about seeing Mexico from the perspective of a bunch of non-Mexicans and Parts Three, Four, Five et cetera see some similar things in some similar ways. Maybe that’s too simple. But it can also get complicated. <br /><br />Let's take one peak at the text: To Amalfitano, exile is “a natural movement, something that in its way helps to abolish fate, or what is generally thought of as fate.” (Let’s not ignore that there is going to be a Part About Fate, which is about a guy called Fate.) Exile is one theme that comes up all over Bolaño’s fiction, and one could refer to all of the instances in which they occur within the novel, but that could end up being a monograph in itself. There are as many themes, motifs, and symbols at play in <i>2666</i> as there are characters, many of which are analogs of someone else who exists elsewhere in the text. Supremely idiosyncratic folk, many of them are. It is hard to begin expressing something cogent about <i>2666</i> without becoming excessive. To me then, <i>2666</i> is one of those novels which acts like a spell book on your life. Motifs enter into reality, and you change. And yet everything stays the same. It’s why I’ll cut myself off here. What’s the point of telling you about magic spells? You wouldn’t believe it without seeing it. Still, the book compels me.<br /><br />One day I'll return to this set of Russian Dolls. For now, just be glad I only really asked you to look at it all from the outside.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8773688449897091691" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


